  "prompt": "Why does ISKCON deny Lord Shiva's Supremacy?",
  "response": "ISKCON (the International Society for Krishna Consciousness) is a Gaudiya Vaishnavism movement that primarily worships Lord Krishna as the Supreme God. In this theological framework, Krishna is considered the original source of all that exists, and all other deities, including Lord Shiva, are seen as subordinate to Him.\n\nHere are some key points regarding ISKCON's perspective on Lord Shiva and the nature of divinity:\n\n1. **Categorization of Divinity**: In the Gaudiya Vaishnava tradition, there is a distinction made between different types of divinity. While Lord Shiva is revered as a great devotee and an important figure in Hindu theology, he is not viewed as the Supreme Being. Instead, he is often seen as a manifestation of God's energy or as a servant of God.\n\n2. **Scriptural References**: ISKCON teachings are primarily based on texts such as the Bhagavad-gita and the Srimad Bhagavatam, which emphasize the supremacy of Krishna. While these texts do acknowledge Lord Shiva's greatness, they do so within a context that positions Krishna as the ultimate source of all existence.\n\n3. **Devotional Focus**: The primary focus of ISKCON's worship and devotion is on Krishna, as the movement's name itself indicates. This is part of a broader theological framework that places Krishna at the center of spiritual practice and understanding.\n\n4. **Respect for Lord Shiva**: It's important to note that ISKCON does not deny the importance of Lord Shiva; instead, it recognizes him as a significant figure in the broader Hindu pantheon. Many ISKCON followers respect and honor Lord Shiva as a great devotee and a representation of certain aspects of the divine.\n\nIn summary, while ISKCON does not grant Lord Shiva the same supreme status as Krishna, it maintains a respectful acknowledgment of his role within the larger context of Hindu spirituality. The movement's emphasis is on Krishna's ultimate superiority within the framework of Gaudiya Vaishnavism.\n",
